In [205]:
# filter data to get only default and fully paid status
df_filtered  = df_filtered[df_filtered['loan_status'].isin(['Fully Paid','Default','Charged Off'])]
df_filtered['issue_year'] = pd.to_datetime(df_filtered['issue_d']).dt.year.astype('int16')
df_filtered['earliest_cr_year'] = df_filtered['earliest_cr_line'].str[-4:].astype('float32')
df_filtered['credit_age'] = (df_filtered['issue_year'] - df_filtered['earliest_cr_year']).astype('int16') # credit age in years
df_filtered['default'] = df['loan_status'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x in ['Default','Charged Off'] else 0 )

Step 2: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

In [214]:
categorical_vars = ['grade', 'home_ownership', 'verification_status', 'purpose']
numerical_vars = ['loan_amnt','annual_inc','dti','fico_range_low','emp_length','term','installment','credit_age','int_rate','revol_util']
bin_counts = [5,5,5,4,5,3,5,5,4,4]
In [215]:
# Create 2x2 grid for categorical plots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(20, 15))
fig.suptitle('', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')

for ax, var in zip(axes.flatten(), categorical_vars):
    # Calculate default rates
    rate_df = df_filtered.groupby(var)['default'].mean().reset_index()
    #rate_df = rate_df.sort_values('default', ascending=False)
    
    # Create bar plot
    sns.barplot(x=var, y='default', data=rate_df, ax=ax, color='skyblue')
    
    # Formatting
    ax.set_title(f'Default Rate by {var}', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel('Default Rate', fontsize=14)
    ax.set_xlabel(var)
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
    ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.3)
    
    # Add value labels
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height():.1%}', 
                   (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
                   ha='center', va='center', 
                   xytext=(0, 10), 
                   textcoords='offset points',
                   fontsize=12)

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96])
plt.show()
In [216]:
# Create 5x2 grid for numerical variables
fig, axes = plt.subplots(5, 2, figsize=(20, 30))
fig.suptitle('', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')

for ax, var, bins in zip(axes.flatten(), numerical_vars, bin_counts):
    # Create bins with range labels
    min_val = df_filtered[var].min()
    max_val = df_filtered[var].max()
    
    # Generate bin edges and labels
    bin_edges = np.linspace(min_val, max_val, bins + 1)
    bin_labels = []
    for i in range(len(bin_edges) - 1):
        label = f"{int(bin_edges[i])}-{int(bin_edges[i+1])}"
        bin_labels.append(label)
    
    # Bin the data
    binned = pd.cut(df_filtered[var], bins=bin_edges, labels=bin_labels, include_lowest=True)
    
    # Calculate default rates
    rate_df = df_filtered.groupby(binned)['default'].mean().reset_index()
    rate_df.columns = [var, 'default_rate']  # Rename for clarity
    
    # Create bar plot
    sns.barplot(x=var, y='default_rate', data=rate_df, ax=ax, palette='rocket', order=bin_labels)
    
    # Formatting
    ax.set_title(f'Default Rate by {var} Range', fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel('Default Rate', fontsize=14)
    ax.set_xlabel(f'{var} Range', fontsize=14)
    ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    
    # Rotate x-labels if needed
    if len(bin_labels[0]) > 8:  # Rotate if labels are long
        ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
    
    # Add value labels
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height():.1%}', 
                   (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
                   ha='center', va='center', 
                   xytext=(0, 10), 
                   textcoords='offset points',
                   fontsize=12)

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96])
plt.show()

Step 3: Modeling¶

In [219]:
# drop installment column as it is highly correlated to loan_amnt
df_filtered_model =  df_filtered_model.drop(columns =['installment'])
df_filtered_model.dropna(inplace = True)
In [221]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from xgboost import XGBClassifier 
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, classification_report, balanced_accuracy_score

# Train-test split
X = df_filtered_model.drop('default', axis=1)
y = df_filtered_model['default']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# Train Random Forest
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=300, max_depth=5, class_weight='balanced', n_jobs=-1)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate
y_pred = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"AUC Score: {auc:.3f}")
print(classification_report(y_test, model.predict(X_test)))

# Feature importance
fi = pd.Series(model.feature_importances_, index=X.columns)
top_features = fi.sort_values(ascending=False).head(5)
print("Top 5 Features:")
print(top_features)

In [225]:
ratio = np.sum(y_train == 0) / np.sum(y_train == 1)
model = XGBClassifier(
    n_estimators      = 400,
    max_depth         = 4,
    learning_rate     = 0.05,
    subsample         = 0.8,
    colsample_bytree  = 0.8,
    objective         = 'binary:logistic',
    eval_metric       = 'auc',
    scale_pos_weight  = ratio,    # tackles imbalance
    random_state      = 42,
    n_jobs            = -1
)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"AUC Score: {auc:.3f}")
print(classification_report(y_test, model.predict(X_test)))
